SIMPLE: refractory
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Refractory
<hw>Re*frac"to*ry</hw> <pr>(-r?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>refractorius</ets>, fr. <ets>refringere</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>refractaire</ets>. See <er>Refract</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Obstinate in disobedience; contumacious; stubborn; unmanageable;
<as>as, a <ex>refractory</ex> child; a <ex>refractory</ex>
beast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Raging appetites that are⟦br⟧
Most disobedient and <qex>refractory</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resisting ordinary treatment; difficult of fusion,
reduction, or the like; -- said especially of metals and the like, which
do not readily yield to heat, or to the hammer; <as>as, a
<ex>refractory</ex> ore</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Perverse; contumacious; unruly; stubborn;
obstinate; unyielding; ungovernable; unmanageable.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refractory</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Refractory
<hw>Re*frac"to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A refractory
person.</def> <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Refractoriness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Jer. TAylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>O<xex>Pottery</xex>) A piece of ware covered with a
vaporable flux and placed in a kiln, to communicate a glaze to the other
articles.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refracture</ent>⟦br⟧
